This is a summary the dataset when its made up only of countries that have at least one year where they were above the mean. In other words, excluding countries that are consistently below the mean.

Examining More Than One Variable

Faceting the data by country shows that there is at least some kind of change over time in many countries, even those that stay well below the median.

These graphs are the count of yearly death totals broken out by year for the entire dataset, not just those countries above the mean.

Notable elements include: starting in about 1999, more countries have higher death rates.

2010 and 2011 have significantly fewer records than in previous years.

Although the introduction of AZT in the 90s began the dramatic decrease of rate of deaths from AIDS, the highest single-year rates are found in the late 2000s. This could be due to better reporting/communication, or an indication of global inequalities in access to medicine.

The same graph as above, but using the dataset of countries with at least one year above the mean.

Although most countries are still reporting deaths on the lower end of the scale, a little more variation is visible, particularly after the late 90s, as compared to the dataset of all countries.

Histograms for number of cases in all countries that have at least one year above the mean for that year.

Despite the introduction of AZT in the 90s, many countries saw increases in reported deaths throughout that decade, likely reflecting differences in medical access.

Showing changes in all above-mean countries. Note that some countries see a sudden sharp rise in 2010, perhaps indicating a new data collection methodology. (A new strain, or sudden change in medicine availability could theoretically explain the change, but overall it seems too high, sudden, and doesnt fit in with the data around it.)

This WHO publication notes the increase in deaths in specific regions of the world in the 2000s, though doesnt account for a sudden leap in 2010. It does, though, note the loss of funding following the global financial crisis in 2008. This could easily have led to loss of treatment options, especially in the poorest parts of the world.

Final Analysis

The first published report identifying HIV/AIDS was published in June 1981. The AIDS epidemic ripped through the globe in the next decade, government mismanagement and fear limiting education and research until the 1990s and the advent of AZT and similar drugs. This data from WHO illustrates the story of the treatment of HIV and AIDS over two decades, from becoming a death sentence to a disease that is treatable and (less) stigmatized.

Authors Note: This project is dedicated to those lost in the epidemic. May their memory be as a blessing.
